WERKSTAAT WOW This neighborhood eatery run by a star of  Manattan’s pre-2K food culture is a thriving, ambitious and distinctive operation we judge the best south of Prospect Park. Austrian street signage and advertisements, as well as a full-size motorcycle mounted over tables in the back room, are the venue’s main design statements . But puckishly, the testosterone-flavored decor matches the locally unparalleled selection of bold draft beers and ciders and liquors and European soft drinks. A grapefruit juice - infused lager quaffs nicely and house cocktails named for faded movie stars from the day in Vienna are more than pleasant. For food, check out the daily chalkboard listings, or ask one of the servers such as charming Crystal for the special entrees. Pork, chicken and fish as schnitzel are staples at WERKSTAAT and quite worthy but much of the delight for diners comes in the sides. Each plays perfectly, in terms of taste, texture and presentation, with the meat or fish. Do not negotiate on swapping sides; you will cheat yourself and possibly annoy chef. WERKSTAAT also makes a statement on it payments, oddly takes only cash or  American Express cards to settle tabs that reflect good value.

Had a really bad interaction with the manager so I will never go back here. My father has recently lost the ability to walk. I've been in the Army for 18 years now and come up to NY once a year to visit the family and we decided to eat here this year. I've also eaten here many times in the past.  When I got to the restaurant I informed the server that I would need to bring my father through the handicap access. I thought that would be as simple as just opening the door and wheeling him in as there was a ramp about 2 feet from the table we were seated at.  A few minutes later and the manager or maybe owner comes over to discuss my request. She starts saying that I didn't tell her that we would need wheelchair access when we made the reservation and had she known that she would have seated us somewhere else. I tried to just agree with her and offer an apology as if it was my oversight. However, she was incessantly complaining over and over about how hard it was going to be to figure out how to wheel him in and seat him. She just kept whining and complaining that we did not let her know.  I didn't know until recently what my father's limitations actually were because his health has deteriorated. Maybe she could have thought to herself for a second of how hard it must be for the family to deal with having their father in this condition and how that compares to this supposedly huge ordeal we were putting her through.  She just assumed that he must have been handicapped his whole life or something and that she was owed some type of explanation. What I didn't understand about the whole situation was it literally just came down to allowing us to open a door and wheel him in about two feet in under 10 seconds.  And to the auto response from the business in advance. Next time just complain to your co-workers. You come off as unprofessional, lazy and ghetto when you start touting, "we're just a small business" directly to the customer as you complain to them about having to do a little work. That's all it came down to, was a little bit of work that you didn't even have to do so I don't know what the problem was.

They do a pretty good job staying authentic. They have a crazy amount of specials, but Id stick to their traditional plates.  Is it as good as Austria? If you want the best Austrian I'd say go to Wallsé, but if the best doesn't worry you, you will enjoy your meal here.
